---
import MainLayout from '../layouts/MainLayout.astro';
---
<MainLayout title="My Homelab | Daniel Castleberry" description="An overview of my personal cybersecurity homelab for research and practice.">
    <h1>My Cybersecurity Homelab</h1>
    <p class="intro">
        This is a multi-segmented environment designed for practical cybersecurity training. It allows me to host services, conduct malware analysis, and practice network defense techniques in a safely isolated setup.
    </p>

    <div class="diagram-container" data-aos="fade-up">
        <img src="/homelab-diagram.png" alt="A network diagram of the homelab setup">
    </div>

    <div class="lab-section" data-aos="fade-up">
        <h2>Network Infrastructure</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Managed Switch:</strong> Forms the core of the lab, enabling traffic segmentation through Virtual LANs (VLANs).</li>
            <li><strong>Raspberry Pi 5 (DNS Sinkhole):</strong> Runs Pi-hole to provide network-wide ad and tracker blocking. All DNS queries are routed through this device to filter malicious domains before they can be accessed.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="lab-section" data-aos="fade-up">
        <h2>Production & Services Network</h2>
        <p>This segment hosts my always-on services and is connected directly to the primary router for external access when needed.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Utility Server (PC):</strong> Functions as a multi-purpose server hosting a web server, a private Minecraft server, and a Network Attached Storage (NAS) for file sharing and backups.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
    
    <div class="lab-section" data-aos="fade-up">
        <h2>Analysis & Research VLAN</h2>
        <p>My primary workstation is isolated on its own VLAN to protect it from other network segments and provide a controlled environment for coursework and sandboxed testing.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Primary Workstation (PC):</strong> My main machine for lab work and university coursework.</li>
            <li><strong>Virtualization:</strong> VMWare Workstation 17 is used to run a variety of virtual machines for safe experimentation.</li>
            <li><strong>Guest VMs:</strong> Kali Linux (for offensive security tools), Ubuntu (for general-purpose testing), and a sandboxed Windows XP instance (for observing malware behavior in a legacy environment).</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="lab-section" data-aos="fade-up">
        <h2>Air-Gapped Malware Detonation Environment</h2>
        <p>For analyzing high-risk malware, I use a physically separate, air-gapped machine with no network connectivity to ensure complete containment.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Hardware:</strong> A dedicated Lenovo laptop.</li>
            <li><strong>Operating System:</strong> Runs Windows XP natively to analyze malware targeting older systems. The entire device is wiped and reimaged after each analysis session to ensure a clean state.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

</MainLayout>

<style>
    .intro { 
        font-size: 1.1rem; 
        max-width: 60ch; 
    }
    .diagram-container {
        margin: 2rem 0;
        text-align: center;
    }
    .diagram-container img {
        max-width: 100%;
        height: auto;
        border-radius: 1rem;
        background: rgba(40, 48, 61, 0.5);
        border: 1px solid var(--border-color);
    }
    .lab-section { 
        margin-bottom: 2.5rem; 
    }
    h2 { 
        color: var(--accent-color); 
        border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); 
        padding-bottom: 0.5rem; 
    }
    p { 
        line-height: 1.6; 
    }
    ul { 
        list-style-type: square; 
        padding-left: 1.5rem; 
    }
    li { 
        margin-bottom: 0.75rem; 
    }
</style>